@x = random_subset(2, -9..9);
@y = random_subset(2, -9..9);
Context("Fraction");
$m[0] = Fraction(($y[1] - $y[0]) / ($x[1] - $x[0]));
# construct parallel line points
do {
  $x[2] = random(-9,9);
  $y[2] = random(-9,9);
} until ($x[2] != $x[0] && ($y[2] - $y[0]) / ($x[2] - $x[0]) != $m[0]);
$d = ($m[0]->value)[1];
$x[3] = $x[2] + non_zero_random(-3,3)*$d;
$y[3] = $y[2] + ($x[3] - $x[2])*$m[0];
@p = map {Point($x[$_],$y[$_])} (0..3);
$choices = DropDown(
  ['same line', 'distinct and parallel', 'perpendicular', 'none of the above'], 1,
  showInStatic => 0
);
Context()->noreduce('(-x)-y', '(-x)+y');
$f[0] = Formula("$m[0]x + ($y[0] - $m[0]*$x[0])")->reduce;
$f[1] = Formula("$m[0]x + ($y[2] - $m[0]*$x[2])")->reduce;

############################################################
# Body
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML
Determine if the two lines are the same line, distinct parallel lines, perpendicular lines, or none of the above.

Line [`\ell_1`] contains the points [`[$p[0]]`] and [`[$p[1]]\text{.}`] Line [`\ell_2`] contains the points [`[$p[2]]`] and [`[$p[3]]\text{.}`]

[_]{$choices}{5}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
The first line's slope is [`[$m[0]]`] and the second line's slope is also [`[$m[0]]\text{.}`] So either the two lines are the same line, or they are parallel.

In point-slope form, the first line has an equation [`y=[$m[0]](x-[$x[0]])+[$y[0]]\text{,}`] and the second line has an equation [`y=[$m[0]](x-[$x[2]])+[$y[2]]\text{.}`] In slope-intercept form, these are [`y=[$f[0]]`] and [`y=[$f[1]]\text{.}`] So the two lines have different [`y`]-intercepts and must be distinct lines.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

